Cape Town - A morning peak hour crash involving two taxis left five people injured in Khayelitsha, Cape Town, on Monday. "Five people were left injured this morning, one of them critically, when two taxis collided on the Lansdowne Road in Khayelitsha in the Western Cape," ER 24 spokesperson Russel Meiring said. "ER24 paramedics, along with the Metro and Life Healthcare, arrived on the scene at approximately 06h10 to find the taxis in the right-hand lane of the road. The occupants had already climbed out of the vehicle and were found lying around on the road. "Paramedics assessed the patients and found that one woman had sustained numerous injuries and was in a critical condition. Two other women were found to have sustained moderate injuries while two men had sustained only minor injuries. "The patients were treated for their injuries and the critically injured woman provided with advanced life support interventions. Once treated, the patients were transported to a nearby provincial hospital for further treatment. "The exact cause of the collision is not yet known but local authorities were on the scene for further investigations," Meiring said.  argusnews@inl.co.za  Cape Argus